          <m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{W= ital "Fd".} {}</m:annotation>
        </m:semantics>
      </m:math>
    </equation><para id="import-auto-id1169736629145">See the symbols as shown in <link target-id="import-auto-id1169738117758"/>. Now force is pressure times area (<m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>F</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>PA</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{F= ital "PA"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>), and so</para><equation id="fs-id1169738176429"><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><mml:mrow xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>W</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>PAd</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext></m:mrow></mml:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{W= ital "PAd"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></equation>
    <para id="import-auto-id1169738200039">Because the volume of a cylinder is its cross-sectional area <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>A</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{A} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> times its length <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>d</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{d} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, we see that <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>Ad</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>Δ</m:mn><m:mi>V</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{ ital "Ad"=ΔV} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, the change in volume; thus,</para>
    <equation id="fs-id1169737994453"><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><mml:mrow xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>W</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mi fontstyle="italic">P</m:mi><m:mn>Δ</m:mn><m:mi>V</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext> (isobaric process).</m:mtext></m:mrow></mml:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{W=PΔV} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></equation>
    <para id="import-auto-id1169737794212">Note that if <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>Δ</m:mn><m:mi>V</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{ΔV} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is positive, then <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>W</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{W} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is positive, meaning that positive work is done by the gas on the outside world.</para><para id="eip-122">(Note that the pressure involved in this work that we’ve called    <m:math>
